# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1977-moscow-bombings
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] A series of three terrorist bombings in Moscow on 8 January 1977 killed seven people and seriously injured 37 others.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] No one claimed responsibility for the bombings, although three members of an Armenian nationalist organization were executed early in 1979 after a KGB investigation and a secret trial.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Some Soviet dissidents said that the suspects had an alibi.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Soon after the event Andrei Sakharov issued a public appeal, expressing concern that the bombings might "be a new provocation on the part of the organs of repression".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] According to historian Jay Bergman, "who actually caused the explosion has never been determined conclusively".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] On 8 January 1977, three bombs were detonated in Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] The first exploded at 17:33 on a crowded train between the Izmailovskaya and Pervomaiskaya stations of the Moscow Metro.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] At 18:05, the second bomb detonated inside a grocery store close to KGB headquarters.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Five minutes later, the third bomb exploded near another grocery store on 25 October Street, just a few hundred meters away from the headquarters of the Communist Party of the Soviet Union.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] At that moment, and for the next two months, there was little public information about the explosions.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] The TASS news agency reported on 10 January 1977 that the explosion was not of great force, "medical help was given to those suffering injury, and an investigation is being conducted".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Later, at meetings of Party activists, it was said that not long before the explosion in the underground on 8 January there had been two other explosions on 25 October Street.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Only on 8 February 1979, after the trial and execution of the three convicted men, did a letter to *Izvestia*, the official newspaper of the Soviet government, indicate that the attacks had killed seven people and injured 37.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] An initial suspect, named Potapov, was arrested in Tambov after setting off a bomb which killed his neighbour's wife and two daughters.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] After being arrested, Potapov confessed that he was also behind the acts of terrorism in Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] However, this turned out to have been a forced confession, and after an investigation lasting one month, this lead was dropped by KGB operatives.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] In October 1977, at Tashkent Airport, a KGB officer noticed a woman carrying a bag similar to a reconstructed picture of a bomb sent by the KGB to all local branches.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] It was discovered that these bags were manufactured only in Yerevan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] In November 1977, Stepan Zatikyan, a founding member of a splinter group of the National United Party, an underground Armenian nationalist organization, was arrested.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] His accomplices, Zaven Bagdasaryan and Hakop Stepanyan, were also taken into custody after an unsuccessful attempt to detonate a bomb at the Kursky Rail Terminal in Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Zatikyan, Stepanyan, and Bagdasaryan were all found guilty on 24 January 1978 and executed five days later.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] The Supreme Court issued a brief statement, dated 31 January 1979, after the trial and execution, naming Zatikyan alone as the perpetrator.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] According to KGB general Philip Bobkov, any publications in Armenia about the bombings were blocked by Karen Demirchyan, the head of Soviet Armenia.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] The 8 January 1977 bombings occurred during systematic reprisals by the Soviet authorities against the Helsinki Groups in Moscow, Ukraine and Lithuania, set up to monitor the USSR's observance of the Helsinki Accords.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] On 10 January 1977, Soviet journalist Victor Louis (Vitaly Yevgenyevich Lui), a well-known KGB agent provocateur, published an article in a British newspaper, hinting at the involvement of Soviet dissidents in the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Several dissidents, including Vladimir Albrekht, the secretary of the Soviet branch of Amnesty International, were threatened and interrogated by the KGB.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] (Soviet dissident Alexander Tarasov claimed to have been interrogated by a KGB investigator who tried to "convince" him that he was involved in the bombing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] In an exchange with the deputy procurator general, he added, "I have serious grounds for concern.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] This is the provocation article in *London Evening News* by Victor Lui.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] These are arrests and interrogations of people who are clearly not related to the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] These are murders of last months, probably committed by the KGB which were not investigated.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] It is enough to mention only two of them: murder of poet Konstantin Bogatyrev and murder of lawyer Evgeni Brunov." After this statement, Sakharov was not only attacked in Soviet newspapers but also received threats by phone.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] Several people tried to break into his apartment, claiming to be relatives of those killed in the metro.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] According to former KGB colonel Oleg Gordievsky, the three Armenians were selected as scapegoats for this terrorist act.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] He wrote, "The case that most alarmed the KGB was the bombing of the Moscow subway by Armenian separatists in 1977.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] In 1982, historians Michel Heller and Alexander Nekrich asserted Zatikyan, Stepanyan, and Bagdasaryan had an alibi supported by multiple witnesses, and their execution was the first political execution in the Soviet Union after the death of Stalin.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] The Armenian dissident Sergei Grigoryants said in 2016 that KGB chief Yuri Andropov and Philipp Bobkov were responsible for the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] On 1 February 1979, the Moscow Helsinki Group made an official statement on the execution of Zatikyan and two unnamed individuals, stating, "The lack of transparency and the whole atmosphere of secrecy give reasons to doubt the validity of charges, objectivity and impartiality of the court".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1977-moscow-bombings] One consequence was the 8 February 1979 letter to Izvestia, denouncing Sakharov and other rights activists as "defenders of murderers".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] The **1996 Kaspiysk bombing** occurred on 16 November 1996 when Chechen terrorists bombed an apartment building in Kaspiysk, Dagestan, killing 68 people.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] The apartment had been built in 1991, and at the time of the bombing around 200 people lived in the housing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] It had been one of the buildings of the Volna boarding house until 1992-1993 when the Caspian border detachment was created and the housing was transferred to city authorities.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] The bombing destroyed the entire nine-story apartment.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] In total, 68 people died, including 21 children.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] The target of the explosion is suspected to be against Russian Border Guard officers who were living inside with their families.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] FSB Director Nikolay Kovalyov stated soon after that a suspect was detained and the identities of two accomplices were known, which was confirmed by the Transcaucasian Border District.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] Ivan Rybkin stated that the people responsible for the attack were opponents of the Chechen peace process, a claim reiterated by the Chechen coalition government.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] It was also estimated that the explosive device had the power of 30-150 kg of TNT.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] Boris Yeltsin declared a national day of mourning in response to the attack.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1996-kaspiysk-bombing] Two days after the attack Viktor Chernomyrdin visited Kaspiysk.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In September 1999, a series of explosions hit four apartment blocks in the Russian cities of Buynaksk, Moscow, and Volgodonsk, killing more than 300, injuring more than 1,000, and spreading a wave of fear across the country.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The bombings, together with the 1999 war of Dagestan, triggered the Second Chechen War.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The handling of the crisis by Vladimir Putin, who was prime minister at the time, boosted his popularity greatly and helped him attain the presidency within a few months.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The blasts hit Buynaksk on 4 September and Moscow on 9 and 13 September.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Another bombing happened in Volgodonsk on 16 September.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Chechen militants were blamed for the bombings, but denied responsibility, along with Chechen president Aslan Maskhadov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A suspicious device resembling those used in the bombings was found and defused in an apartment block in the Russian city of Ryazan on 22 September.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 23 September, Vladimir Putin even praised the vigilance of the inhabitants of Ryazan and ordered the air bombing of Grozny, which marked the beginning of the Second Chechen War.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Three Russian Federal Security Service (FSB) agents who had planted the devices at Ryazan were arrested by the local police.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The next day, FSB director Nikolai Patrushev announced that the incident in Ryazan had been an anti-terror drill and the device found there contained only sugar, and freed the FSB agents involved.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The official investigation of the Buynaksk bombing was completed in 2001, while the investigations of the Moscow and Volgodonsk bombings were completed in 2002.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In 2000, seven people were convicted of perpetrating the Buynaksk attack.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to the court ruling on the Moscow and Volgodonsk bombings, which was announced in 2004, the attacks were organized and led by Achemez Gochiyaev, who remains at large.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] All bombings, the court ruled, were ordered by Islamist warlords Ibn Al-Khattab and Abu Omar al-Saif, who have been killed.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Five other suspects have been killed and six have been convicted by Russian courts on terrorism-related charges.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Attempts at an independent investigation faced obstruction from the Russian government.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] State Duma deputy Yuri Shchekochikhin filed two motions for a parliamentary investigation of the events, but the motions were rejected by the State Duma in March 2000.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] An independent public commission to investigate the bombings was chaired by Duma deputy Sergei Kovalev.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The commission was rendered ineffective because of the government's refusal to respond to its inquiries.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Two key members of the Kovalev Commission, Sergei Yushenkov and Yuri Shchekochikhin, have since died in apparent assassinations.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The commission's lawyer and investigator Mikhail Trepashkin was arrested and served four years in prison "for revealing state secrets".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Although the bombings were widely blamed on Chechen terrorists, their guilt was never conclusively proven.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A number of historians and investigative journalists have instead called the bombings a false flag attack perpetrated by Russian state security services to win public support for a new war in Chechnya and to boost the popularity of Vladimir Putin prior to the upcoming presidential elections.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Former FSB agent Alexander Litvinenko, who blamed the FSB for the bombings and was a critic of Putin, was assassinated in London in 2006.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A British inquiry later determined that Litvinenko's murder was "probably" carried out with the approval of Vladimir Putin and Nikolai Patrushev.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In July 1999, Russian journalist Aleksandr Zhilin, writing in the *Moskovskaya Pravda*, warned that there would be terrorist attacks in Moscow organised by the government.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Using a leaked Kremlin document as evidence, he added that the motive would be to undermine the opponents of the Russian president Boris Yeltsin.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] These included Moscow mayor Yury Luzhkov and former prime minister Yevgeny Primakov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to Amy Knight, "even more significant is the fact that a respected and influential Duma deputy, Konstantin Borovoi, was told on September 9, the day of the first Moscow apartment bombing, that there was to be a terrorist attack in the city.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] His source was an officer of the Russian military intelligence (GRU).
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 7 August 1999, an Islamist group, led by Shamil Basayev and Ibn al-Khattab, invaded the Russian republic of Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The war in Dagestan was allegedly planned in advance by the Russian government to justify starting the war in Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] However, the initial plan included only a limited campaign to occupy the northern third of Chechnya up to the Terek River valley.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] After the apartment bombings, Putin approved a more ambitious campaign to subdue all of Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Four apartment bombings took place and at least three attempted bombings were prevented.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] All bombings had the same "signature", based on the nature and the volume of the destruction.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In each case a powerful explosive was used, and the timers were set to go off at night and inflict the maximum number of civilian casualties.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The explosives were placed to destroy the weakest, most critical elements of the buildings and force them to "collapse like a house of cards".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The individuals behind the bombings were able to obtain or manufacture several tons of powerful explosives and deliver them to numerous destinations across Russia.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 31 August 1999, at 20:00 local time, a bomb exploded in the amusement arcade of the Manezh Square shopping complex of Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to the FSB, the explosion had been caused by a bomb of about 300 grams of explosives.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 2 September 1999, an unknown person called and claimed that the bombing was committed by the militant organization the "Liberation Army of Dagestan".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 4 September 1999, at 22:00, a car bomb detonated outside a five-story apartment building in the city of Buynaksk in Dagestan, near the border of Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The building was housing Russian border guard soldiers and their families.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Sixty-four people were killed and 133 were injured in the explosion.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 4 September 1999, another bomb was discovered shortly after the explosion in the city of Buynaksk in Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The defused bomb was in a car containing 2,706 kilograms (5,966 lb) of explosive material.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] It was discovered by local residents in a parking lot surrounded by an army hospital and residential buildings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 9 September 1999, shortly after midnight at 20:00 GMT, a bomb detonated on the ground floor of an apartment building in southeast Moscow (19 Guryanova Street).
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The explosive power was equivalent to 300–400 kilograms (660–880 lb) of TNT.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The nine-story building was destroyed, killing 106 people inside (with early reports giving 93 dead) and injuring 249 others, and damaging 19 nearby buildings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A total of 108 apartments were destroyed during the bombing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] An FSB spokesman announced that traces of RDX and TNT were found on items removed from the site of the explosion.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Residents said a few minutes before the blast four men were seen speeding away from the building in a car.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The FSB declared the bombing a terrorist attack the following morning, 10 September 1999.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] That day, Vladimir Putin was due to fly to Auckland for the 1999 APEC summit; after a brief consultation with Boris Yeltsin, it was decided that the trip go ahead as planned.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Yeltsin had originally intended to go himself, but reasoned to Bill Clinton that Putin would almost certainly be president himself by the year 2000, contrary to speculation over Yeltsin's successor.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Prior to his flight, Putin telephoned Clinton and claimed he had "every reason to believe" that Chechen extremists were not only behind the attacks but had links to the Al-Qaeda group which had perpetrated the bombings of the U.S. embassies in Nairobi and Dar es Salaam the previous year.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Putin and Clinton would have their first face-to-face meeting in Auckland the following day, and Putin flew back shortly afterward.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Yeltsin ordered the search of 30,000 residential buildings in Moscow for explosives.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] He took personal control of the investigation of the blast.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Putin declared 13 September a day of mourning for the victims of the attacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 13 September 1999, at 05:00, a large bomb exploded in a basement of an apartment block on Kashirskoye Highway in southern Moscow, about 6 kilometres (3.7 mi) from the place of the last attack.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] This was the deadliest blast in the chain of bombings (because the apartment was built with brick), with 119 people killed and 200 injured.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The eight-story building was flattened, littering the street with debris and throwing some concrete pieces hundreds of meters away.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 13 September 1999, a local businessman Achemez Gochiyaev called to police and reported about bombs located in apartment blocks on Borisovskiye Prudy and Kapotnya in Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Gochiyaev claimed that he was framed by his old acquaintance, an FSB officer who asked him to rent basements "as storage facilities" at four locations where bombs were later found.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] After the second explosion on Kashirskoye highway Gochiyaev realized he was set up, called the police and told them about the basements of two other buildings at Borisovskie Prudy and Kapotnya, where the explosives were actually found and explosions averted.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In 2002 Felshtinsky and Litvinenko obtained a written testimony from Achemez Gochiyaev as well as a video recording and several photographs about it.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The statement by Gochiyaev was also received by Prima News agency.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 13 September, just hours after the second explosion in Moscow, Russian Duma speaker Gennadiy Seleznyov of the Communist Party made an announcement, "I have just received a report.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to information from Rostov-on-Don, an apartment building in the city of Volgodonsk was blown up last night." When the Volgodonsk bombing happened on 16 September, Vladimir Zhirinovsky questioned Seleznyov in the Duma the following day, but Seleznyov turned his microphone off.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Later, Seleznyov said it was a misunderstanding, and he actually referred to an explosion organized by criminal gangs which took place in Volgodonsk on 12 September.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to Philip Short, Seleznyov made an announcement based on a wire service message about an explosion which took place in Volgodonsk on 12 September and killed one person.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] At the time it was thought that this (smaller and eventually found to be unrelated) explosion was another in the same series as the preceding ones in Moscow and Buynaksk.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Alexander Litvinenko believed that someone had mixed up the order of the blasts, "the usual *Kontora* mess up".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to Litvinenko, "Moscow-2 was on the 13th and Volgodonsk on 16th, but they got it to the speaker the other way around".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Investigator Mikhail Trepashkin said that the man who gave Seleznyov the note was indeed an FSB officer.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A truck bomb exploded on 16 September 1999, outside a nine-story apartment complex in the southern Russian city of Volgodonsk, killing 17 people and injuring 69.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Surrounding buildings were also damaged.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The blast also happened 14 km (9 mi) from a nuclear power plant.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Prime Minister Vladimir Putin signed a decree calling on law enforcement and other agencies to develop plans within three days to protect industry, transportation, communications, food processing centres and nuclear complexes.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] At 20:30 on 22 September 1999, Alexei Kartofelnikov, a resident of an apartment building in the city of Ryazan noticed two suspicious men who carried sacks into the basement from a car.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] While the license plate indicated that the car was registered in Moscow, a sheet of paper was taped over the last two digits, and the number written on it implied that the car was local.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Kartofelnikov alerted the police, but by the time they arrived the car and the men were gone.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The policemen found three sacks of white powder in the basement, each weighing 50 kg (110 lb).
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A detonator and a timing device were attached to the sacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The detonator was reported by a Russian newspaper to be a 12-gauge shotgun shell filled with powder.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Yuri Tkachenko, the head of the local bomb squad, disconnected the detonator and the timer.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Reportedly, Tkachenko tested the three sacks of white substance with a "MO-2" gas analyser, which detected RDX vapors.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Inhabitants of the apartment building were evacuated.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to David Satter, residents of neighboring buildings fled their homes in terror, to the effect that nearly 30,000 residents spent the night on the street.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Police and rescue vehicles converged from different parts of the city.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] As many as 1,200 local police officers were put on alert, the railroad stations and the airport were surrounded, and roadblocks were set up on highways leaving the city.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] At 01:30 on 23 September 1999, explosive engineers of the Ryazan UFSB took a sample of substance from the suspicious-looking sacks to a firing ground located about 1.6 km (1 mi) away from Ryazan for testing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] During the substance tests at that area they tried to explode it by means of a detonator, which was also made from a shotgun shell, but the substance failed to detonate.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] At 05:00, Radio Rossiya reported about the attempted bombing, noting that the bomb was set up to go off at 05:30.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In the morning, Ryazan resembled a city under siege.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Composite sketches of three suspected terrorists, two men and a woman, were posted everywhere in the city and shown on TV.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] At 08:00 Russian television reported the attempt to blow out the building in Ryazan and identified the explosive used in the bomb as RDX.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Vladimir Rushailo announced later that police prevented a terrorist act.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A news report at 16:00 reported that the explosives failed to detonate during their testing outside the city.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] At 19:00, Vladimir Putin praised the vigilance of the inhabitants of Ryazan, and called for the air bombing of the Chechen capital Grozny in response to the terrorism acts.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 23 September Natalia Yukhnova, a telephone service employee in Ryazan, tapped into a suspicious phone call to Moscow and overheard the following instruction: "Leave one at a time, there are patrols everywhere".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The called number was traced to a telephone exchange unit serving FSB offices.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] When arrested, the detainees produced FSB identification cards.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] They were soon released on orders from Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The position of Russian authorities on the Ryazan incident changed significantly over time.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Initially, it was declared by the FSB and federal government to be a real threat.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] However, after the people who planted the bomb were identified, the official version changed to "security training".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 24 September, FSB director Nikolai Patrushev announced that it was an exercise that was being carried out to test responses after the earlier blasts.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] FSB also issued a public apology about the incident.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In a show *Independent Investigation* on NTV, Evgeniy Savostyanov, former director of Moscow and Moscow Oblast regional FSB branch, has criticized the FSB for performing such exercise on residential buildings with inhabitants inside and without notifying local authorities.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In excerpts from the planned Ryazan operation, first published in 2002, it was stated that the exercise was overseen by the head of the FSB's Center of Special Operations (CSO), Major General Alexander Tikhonov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In February 2000, *Novaya Gazeta* journalist Pavel Voloshin published an essay entitled *What happened in Ryazan: Sugar or Hexogen?*, that was partly based on his two-hour long interview with Yuri Tkachenko, the police explosives expert who defused the Ryazan bomb.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The essay noted that it's well known that a gas analyser that tested the vapours coming from the sacks indicated the presence of RDX.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Tkachenko said that he was completely certain that the instrument was in correct working order.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The gas analyser was of world-class quality, cost $20,000, and was maintained by a specialist who worked according to a strict schedule, making frequent prophylactic checks, because the device contained a radioactive source.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Meticulous care in the handling of the gas analyser was a necessity because the lives of the bomb squad experts depended on the reliability of their equipment.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Speaking of the detonator, Voloshin noted that people who disarmed the device (Tkachenko and his bomb squad) claimed that the detonator attached to the sacks was not a dummy and had been prepared on a professional level.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The police warrant officer who answered the original call and discovered the bomb insisted that there were no doubts it was a combat situation.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In March 2000, *Novaya Gazeta* journalist Pavel Voloshin reported the account of Private Alexei P.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] (later identified as Pinyaev) of the 137th Guards Airborne Regiment.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Pinyaev guarded a storehouse with weapons and ammunition near the city of Ryazan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Together with a friend, he entered the storehouse to see the weapons.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The friends were surprised to see that the storehouse contained sacks with the word "sugar" on them.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Pinyaev and his friend were discouraged, but didn't want to leave the storehouse empty-handed.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The two paratroopers cut a hole in one of the bags and put some sugar in a plastic bag.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] They made tea with the sugar, but the taste of the tea was terrible.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] They became frightened because the substance might turn out to be saltpeter, and brought the plastic bag to a platoon commander.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] He consulted a sapper, who identified the substance as hexogen.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] A report aired by *ORT* in March 2000 and created by journalist Leonid Grozin and operator Dmitry Vishnevoy accused *Novaya Gazeta* of lying.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to Grozin and Vishnevoy, there is no storehouse at the test range of the 137th Regiment.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Alexei Pinyaev has admitted meeting with Pavel Voloshin, but claimed that he was merely asked to confirm a pre-conceived story.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] At an FSB press conference in 2001, Private Pinyayev stated that there was no hexogen in the 137th Airborne Regiment and that he was hospitalised in December 1999 and no longer visited the test range.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] After the bombing at Guryanova Street on 9 September, the Moscow FSB reported that items removed from the scene showed traces of TNT and RDX (or "hexogen") explosives.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] However, FSB has declared later that the explosives used in the bombings were a mixture of aluminium powder, ammonium nitrate, TNT and sugar prepared by the perpetrators in a concrete mixer at a fertiliser factory in Urus-Martan, Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Also, each bomb contained some plastic explosive used as an explosive booster.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] RDX is produced in only one factory in Russia, in the city of Perm.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to David Satter, the FSB changed the story about the type of explosive, since it was difficult to explain how huge amounts of RDX disappeared from the closely guarded Perm facility.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Multiple survivors of the bombings have developed disabilities, with many of them diagnosed with post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In 2006, Irina Khalai, a survivor of the Volgodonsk bombing, founded the NGO "Volga-Don", which promotes legislation for the legal recognition of victims of terrorist attacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] He said that the explosions in Buynaksk and Moscow were carried out by his organisation.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to him, the attacks were a retaliation to the deaths of Muslim women and children during Russian air raids in Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] "We will answer death with death," the caller said.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Russian officials from both the Interior Ministry and FSB, at the time, expressed scepticism over the claims and said there is no such organization.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 15 September 1999, a Dagestani official also denied the existence of a "Dagestan Liberation Army".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In an interview published in Lidove Noviny on 9 September, Shamil Basayev denied responsibility for the bombings and said that it had been the work of Dagestanis.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to Basayev, the bombings were a retribution for the military operation of the Russian Army against "three small villages" in Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In subsequent interviews, Basayev said he did not know who perpetrated the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In a 12 September interview with Associated Press, Ibn al-Khattab said that "From now on they will get our bombs everywhere!
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Let Russia await our explosions blasting through their cities!
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] I swear we will do it!" However, in a subsequent interview on 14 September to the Interfax agency in Grozny, Khattab denied responsibility for the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Chechen Foreign Ministry issued an official statement on 14 September condemning Moscow blasts, and affirming that "Ichkeria stands firmly against terrorism in any manifestation".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In February 2000, the US Secretary of State Madeleine Albright stated they have not seen any evidence that ties the bombings to Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In 2000, investigation of the Buynaksk attack was completed and seven people were convicted of the bombing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Russia's pre-trial investigation of the Moscow and Volgodonsk bombings was finished in 2002.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to the Russian State Prosecutor office, all apartment bombings were executed under command of ethnic Karachay Achemez Gochiyayev and planned by Ibn al-Khattab and Abu Omar al-Saif, Arab militants fighting in Chechnya on the side of Chechen insurgents.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Al-Khattab and al-Saif were killed during the Second Chechen War.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to investigators, the explosives were prepared at a fertiliser factory in Urus-Martan Chechnya, by "mixing aluminium powder, nitre and sugar in a concrete mixer", or by also putting there RDX and TNT.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] From there they were sent to a food storage facility in Kislovodsk, which was managed by an uncle of one of the terrorists, Yusuf Krymshakhalov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Another conspirator, Ruslan Magayayev, leased a KamAZ truck in which the sacks were stored for two months.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] After everything was planned, the participants were organised into several groups which then transported the explosives to different cities.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to investigators, the explosion in Moscow mall on 31 August was committed by another man, Magomed-Zagir Garzhikaev on the orders from Shamil Basayev, according to the FSB.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Court hearings on the Moscow and Volgodonsk attacks were held behind closed doors, and were completed in 2004.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The process has produced 90 volumes of proceedings, five of which were classified.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to the court ruling, Al-Khattab paid Gochiyayev $500,000 to carry out the attacks at Guryanova Street, Kashirskoye Highway, and Borisovskiye Prudy, and then helped to hide Gochiyayev and his accomplices in Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In early September 1999, Magayayev, Krymshamkhalov, Batchayev and Dekkushev reloaded the cargo into a Mercedes-Benz 2236 trailer and delivered it to Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] En route, they were protected from possible complications by an accomplice, Khakim Abayev, who accompanied the trailer in another car.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In Moscow they were met by Achemez Gochiyayev, who registered in Hotel Altai under the fake name "Laipanov", and Denis Saitakov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The explosives were left in a warehouse in Ulitsa Krasnodonskaya, which was leased by pseudo-Laipanov (Gochiyayev).
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The next day, the explosives were delivered in "ZIL-5301" vans to three addresses—Ulitsa Guryanova, Kashirskoye Shosse and Ulitsa Borisovskiye Prudy, where pseudo-Laipanov leased cellars.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Gochiyayev supervised the placement of the bombs in the rented cellars.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Next followed the explosions at the former two addresses.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The explosion at 16 Borisovskiye Prudy was prevented.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to the court, 4 September Buinaksk bombing was ordered by Al-Khattab.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Reportedly, since the perpetrators have managed to explode only one truck bomb instead of the two, Khattab called it a "botched job" and paid $300,000 for it, which was a part of the sum he originally promised.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] One of the suspects confessed having loaded the trucks with sacks in Buynaksk, but claimed he did not know what they were intended for.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The explosion in the mall on Manezhnaya Square was the subject of a separate court process held in Moscow in 2009.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Adam Dekkushev and Yusuf Krymshakhalov have both been sentenced to life terms in a special regime colony.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Both defendants have pleaded guilty only to some of the charges.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Dekkushev acknowledged that he knew the explosives he transported were to be used for an act of terror.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Dekkushev also confirmed Gochiyaev's role in the attacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Dekkushev was extradited to Russia on 14 April 2002 to stand trial.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Krymshakhalov was apprehended and extradicted to Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Achemez Gochiyaev, allegedly the head of the group that carried out the attacks, remains a fugitive, and is under an international search warrant.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In September 1999, hundreds of Chechen nationals (out of the more than 100,000 permanently living in Moscow) were briefly detained and interrogated in Moscow, as a wave of anti-Chechen sentiments swept the city.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] However, no Chechens were tried for the Buinaksk, Moscow or Volgodonsk attacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Rather, it were Dagestani Wahhabis in the case of the Buinaksk bombing, and Karachay Wahhabis in the case of Moscow and Volgodonsk attacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The Russian Duma rejected two motions for a parliamentary investigation of the Ryazan incident.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In the Duma a pro-Kremlin party Unity, voted to seal all materials related to the Ryazan incident for the next 75 years and forbade an investigation into what happened.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] An independent public commission to investigate the bombings was chaired by Duma deputy Sergei Kovalyov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The commission started its work in February 2002.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 5 March Sergei Yushenkov and Duma member Yuli Rybakov flew to London where they met Alexander Litvinenko and Mikhail Trepashkin.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] After this meeting, Trepashkin began working with the commission.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] However, the public commission was rendered ineffective because of government refusal to respond to its inquiries.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Two key members of the commission, Sergei Yushenkov and Yuri Shchekochikhin, both Duma members, have died in apparent assassinations in April 2003 and July 2003, respectively.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Another member of the commission, Otto Lacis, was assaulted in November 2003 and two years later, on 3 November 2005, he died in a hospital after a car accident.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The commission asked lawyer Mikhail Trepashkin to investigate the case.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Trepashkin said he found that the basement of one of the bombed buildings was rented by FSB officer Vladimir Romanovich and that the latter was witnessed by several people.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Trepashkin also investigated a letter attributed to Achemez Gochiyayev and found that the alleged assistant of Gochiyayev who arranged the delivery of sacks might have been Kapstroi-2000 vice president Alexander Karmishin, a resident of Vyazma.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Trepashkin was unable to bring the alleged evidence to the court because he was arrested in October 2003 (on charges of illegal arms possession) and imprisoned in Nizhny Tagil, just a few days before he was to make his findings public.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] He was sentenced by a Moscow military closed court to four years imprisonment on a charge of revealing state secrets.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In a letter to Olga Konskaya, Trepashkin wrote that some time before the bombings, Moscow's Regional Directorate against Organized Crimes (RUOP GUVD) arrested several people for selling the explosive RDX.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Following that, Nikolai Patrushev's Directorate of FSB officers came to the GUVD headquarters, captured evidence and ordered the investigators fired.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Trepashkin wrote that he learned about the story at a meeting with several RUOP officers in the year 2000.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] They claimed that their colleagues could present eyewitness accounts in a court.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] They offered a video tape with evidence against the RDX dealers.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Mr Trepashkin did not publicise the meeting fearing for lives of the witnesses and their families.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] According to Trepashkin, his supervisors and the people from the FSB promised not to arrest him if he left the Kovalev commission and started working together with the FSB "against Alexander Litvinenko".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 24 March 2000, two days before the presidential elections, NTV Russia featured the Ryazan events of Fall 1999 in the talk show *Independent Investigation*.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] The talk with the residents of the Ryazan apartment building along with FSB public relations director Alexander Zdanovich and Ryazan branch head Alexander Sergeyev was filmed few days earlier.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] On 26 March, Boris Nemtsov voiced his concern over the possible shut-down of NTV for airing the talk.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Seven months later, NTV general manager Igor Malashenko said at the JFK School of Government that Information Minister Mikhail Lesin warned him on several occasions.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Malashenko's recollection of Lesin's warning was that by airing the talk show NTV "crossed the line" and that the NTV managers were "outlaws" in the eyes of the Kremlin.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Malashenko told him that Valentin Yumashev brought a warning from the Kremlin, one day before airing the show, promising in no uncertain terms that the NTV managers "should consider themselves finished" if they went ahead with the broadcast.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Artyom Borovik was among the people who investigated the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] He received numerous death threats and died in a suspicious plane crash in March 2000 that was regarded by Felshtinsky and Pribylovsky as a probable assassination.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Journalist Anna Politkovskaya and former security service member Alexander Litvinenko, who investigated the bombings, were killed in 2006.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Surviving victims of the Guryanova street bombing asked President Dmitry Medvedev to resume the official investigation in 2008, but it was not resumed.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] In a 2017 discussion at the RFE/RL Sergei Kovalyov said: "I think that the Chechen trace was skilfully fabricated.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] No one from the people who organized the bombings was found, and no one actually was looking for them".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] He then was asked by Vladimir Kara-Murza if he believes that several key members of his commission, and even Boris Berezovskiy and Boris Nemtsov who "knew quite a few things about the bombings" were killed to prevent the independent investigation.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Kovalev responded: "I cannot state with full confidence that the explosions were organized by the authorities.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] Although it's clear that the explosions were useful for them, useful for future president Vladimir Vladimirovich Putin, because he had just promised to "waste in the outhouse" (as he said) everyone who had any relation to terrorism.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] It was politically beneficial for him to scare people with terrorism.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p01] But what can be stated with full confidence is this: the investigation of both the Moscow explosions and the so-called "exercises" in Ryazan is trumped up.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Some of them described the bombings as typical "active measures" practised by the KGB in the past.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The theory of Russian government involvement has been described in a number of books and movies on the subject.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] In another book, *Lubyanka Criminal Group*, Litvinenko and Alexander Goldfarb described the transformation of the FSB into a criminal and terrorist organization, including conducting the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] (Litvinenko 2002) Former GRU analyst and historian Viktor Suvorov said that the book describes "a leading criminal group that provides "protection" for all other organized crime in the country and which continues the criminal war against their own people", like their predecessors NKVD and KGB.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] He added: "The book proves: Lubyanka [the KGB headquarters] was taken over by enemies of the people. ...
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] If Putin's team can not disprove the facts provided by Litvinenko, Putin must shoot himself.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Alexander Goldfarb and Marina Litvinenko published a book *Death of a Dissident*.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Litvinenko was "the most compelling proof" of the FSB involvement theory.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] A documentary film *Assassination of Russia* was made in 2000 by two French producers who had previously worked on NTV's *Sugar of Ryazan* program.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] A documentary *Nedoverie* ("Disbelief") about the bombing controversy made by Russian director Andrei Nekrasov was premiered at the 2004 Sundance Film Festival.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The film chronicles the story of Tatyana and Alyona Morozova, the two Russian-American sisters, who had lost their mother in the attack, and decided to find out who did it.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] His next film on the subject was *Rebellion: the Litvinenko Case*.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Yuli Dubov, author of *The Big Slice*, wrote a novel *The Lesser Evil*, based on the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The main characters of the story are *Platon* (Boris Berezovsky) and *Larry* (Badri Patarkatsishvili).
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] They struggle against an evil KGB officer, *Old man* (apparently inspired by the legendary Philipp Bobkov), who brings another KGB officer, *Fedor Fedorovich* (Vladimir Putin) to power by staging a series of apartment bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The view about the bombings being organized and perpetrated by Russian state security services was originally put forward by journalist David Satter and historians Yuri Felshtinsky and Vladimir Pribylovsky, in co-authorship with Alexander Litvinenko.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] It was later supported by a number of historians.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] In her book *Putin's Kleptocracy*, historian Karen Dawisha summarized evidence related to the bombings and concluded that "to blow up your own innocent and sleeping people in your capital city is an action almost unthinkable.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Yet the evidence that the FSB was at least involved in planting a bomb in Ryazan is incontrovertible." According to Timothy Snyder, "it seemed possible" that the perpetrators of the apartment bombings were FSB officers.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] David Satter considered the bombings as a political provocation by the Russian secret services that was similar to the burning of the Reichstag.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] This view has been also supported by investigative journalists.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Former Russian State Security Council chief Alexandr Lebed in his 29 September 1999 interview with *Le Figaro* said he was almost convinced that the government organised the terrorist acts.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Andrei Illarionov, a former key economic adviser to the Russian president, said that FSB involvement "is not a theory, it is a fact.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] There is no other element that could have organized the bombings except for the FSB." Later Lebed's public relations staff claimed that he was quoted out of the context.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Some US politicians have commented that they consider credible the allegations about Russian state security services as the actual organizers of the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] In 2003, U.S. senator John McCain said that "It was during Mr.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Putin's tenure as Prime Minister in 1999 that he launched the Second Chechen War following the Moscow apartment bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] There remain credible allegations that Russia's FSB had a hand in carrying out these attacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] On 11 January 2017, senator Marco Rubio raised the issue of the 1999 bombings during the confirmation hearings for Rex Tillerson.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] According to Satter, all four bombings that occurred had a similar "signature" which indicated that the explosives had been carefully prepared, a mark of skilled specialists.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The terrorists were able to obtain tons of hexogen explosive and transport it to various locations in Russia; hexogen is produced in one plant in Perm Oblast for whose security the central FSB is responsible.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The culprits would also have needed to organise nine explosions (the four that occurred and the five attempted bombings reported by the authorities) in different cities in a two-week period.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Satter's estimate for the time required for target plan development, site visits, explosives preparation, renting space at the sites and transporting explosives to the sites was four to four and a half months.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Hexogen was however at this time also widely available in Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] In a speech to the Oxford Union on 12 March 2022, former MI6 officer Christopher Steele voiced support for the idea that the bombings were a false flag operation conducted by Russian security services in order to justify the war in Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] According to Russian investigative journalist Andrei Soldatov, "From the start, it seemed that the Kremlin was determined to suppress all discussion ...
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] When Alexander Podrabinek, a Russian human rights activist, tried to import copies of Litvinenko's and Felshtinsky's *Blowing up Russia* in 2003, they were confiscated by the FSB.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Trepashkin himself, acting as a lawyer for two relatives of the victims of the blast, was unable to obtain information he requested and was entitled to see by law".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] However, Soldatov believed that the obstruction might reflect "'paranoia' rather than guilt on the part of the authorities".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Consequently, Soldatov argued, that paranoia has produced the very conspiracy theories that the Russian Government intended to eradicate.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] In their book *The New Nobility*, Andrei Soldatov and Irina Borogan believe that the Ryazan incident had actually been a training exercise by Vympel, a counter-terrorism FSB unit.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Soldatov and Borogan noted that, according to Russian state security services, Achemez Gochiyaev was not an innocent businessman, but a leader of a local Islamist group since the mid-1990s, together with Dekkushev and Krymshamkhalov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Soldatov and Borogan have also noted a partial admission of guilt by Dekkushev and Krymshamkhalov after their interrogations during a trial in 2003.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Ware points out that that would explain the timing of the attacks, and why there were no attacks after the date on which the insurgents were driven from Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] It would also explain why no Chechen claimed responsibility.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Also it would explain Basayev's reference to responsibility of Dagestanis and it would be consistent with the initial vow of Khattab to set off the bombs blasting through Russian cities.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Pope in his review of David Satter's book *Darkness at Dawn* cited Kirill Pankratov's criticism, published as a contribution to Johnson's Russia List.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Regarding the apartment bombings, Pankratov argued that the Russian authorities did not need an additional justification to wage a war against Chechnya, in view of high-profile kidnappings and the invasion of Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Political scientist Brian Taylor believes that there is too little evidence to decide which version of the events is correct, as the available evidence is fragmentary and controversial.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Taylor identifies several reasons to doubt the conspiracy version.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] First, while the bombings did propel Putin to power, that alone is not proof that this was the goal of the attacks.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Second, there was a *casus belli* even without the bombings—namely, the invasion of Dagestan and multiple kidnappings in the region in the preceding years.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Third, if the goal of the bombings was to justify a new war, one or two bombings in Moscow would be more than adequate; any subsequent bombings would be potentially dangerous, because they would increase the risk to expose the conspiracy.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Fourth, a complex plot involving multiple players and a large number of FSB operatives could not be kept secret.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] According to Taylor, it is plausible that the FSB "simulated" an attack in Ryazan in order to claim credit for "uncovering" it; however, the plot was foiled by vigilant local denizens and law enforcement personnel, and the "training exercise" justification was improvised after the plot failed.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Max Abrahms, a researcher who is critical of the efficacy of terrorism in general, argued that the bombings were detrimental for the self-determination of Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] He noted that the Chechen Republic of Ichkeria has achieved a de facto independence from Russia after the Khasavyurt Accord, with two thirds of Russian citizens favoring the separation of the breakaway republic.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] However, the public opinion in Russia has changed dramatically after the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Most Russians started "baying for blood" and strongly supporting the war with Chechnya that became inevitable and led to the loss of the independence as a result of the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] According to Abrahms, this supports his theory that attacks by terrorist organizations have been always counterproductive for the perpetrators and therefore gave rise to conspiracy theories about alternative perpetrators who actually benefited from the events.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] In March 2000, Putin dismissed the allegations of FSB involvement in the bombings as "delirious nonsense." "There are no people in the Russian secret services who would be capable of such crime against their own people.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The very allegation is immoral," he said.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] An FSB spokesman said that "Litvinenko's evidence cannot be taken seriously by those who are investigating the bombings".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Yuri Luzhkov, Mayor of Moscow at the time of the bombings, believed that the bombings in Moscow were facilitated by new legislation that established freedom of movement within the country, which was restricted prior to 1993.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] According to Luzhkov, the law made it possible for Chechen terrorists to bring weapons to Moscow and store them there, as well as purchase vehicles and provide housing for their personnel who had arrived in Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] According to Luzhkov, "for three months, after having arrived in Moscow, a terrorist could live wherever he wanted and stay with anyone, without notifying the police", which allowed the terrorists to prepare the bombings.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] On 14 July 2014, David Satter filed Freedom of Information Act (FOIA) requests with the State Department, the CIA and the FBI, inquiring about documents pertaining to the apartment bombings, the Ryazan incident and persons who tried to investigate the bombings and were killed.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The agencies acknowledged receipt of the requests, but Satter received no other response within the statutory time limit.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] Satter filed suit against the Department of Justice and other agencies involved on 29 August 2014.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] The State Department responded with a redacted copy of a cable from the U.S. embassy in Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] David Satter made a renewed FOIA request, and on 22 March 2017, State Department responded that documents concerning the U.S. assessment of the bombings would remain secret.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-russian-apartment-bombings-p02] A draft Vaughn index, a document used by agencies to justify withholdings in FOIA cases, said that the release of that information had "the potential to inject friction into or cause serious damage" to relationships with the Russian government that were "vital to U.S. national security".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] The **1999 Vladikavkaz bombing** took place in a crowded market in Vladikavkaz, North Ossetia–Alania, Russia on 19 March 1999, killing 52 and injuring 168.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] The bombers were tried and convicted on 15 December 2003.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] The court also convicted the men of the bombing of a military housing unit known as "Sputnik" on 18 May 1999 that left four dead and 17 injured and a Vladikavkaz train station on 28 June 1999, which injured 18 people.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] In addition, the court found the men guilty in the kidnapping of four Russian officers and taking them to Chechnya for ransom on 30 July 1999.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] On 21 March 1999, a day of national mourning was declared in Russia for the victims, as a fire had occurred the previous day at a psychiatric hospital in Vologda Oblast.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] As a result of the terrorist attack, the football match between the national teams of Russia and Andorra was moved from Vladikavkaz to Moscow at the request of the Andorran side[3].
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] The incident also affected the match schedule of Vladikavkaz's football club *Alania* in the Russian Championship, prompting increased security measures ahead of their first-round match against *Spartak Moscow*.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] On 15 December 2003, the Supreme Court of North Ossetia delivered its verdict in the terrorism case.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] Adam Tsurov was sentenced to life imprisonment in a high-security penal colony, while Makhmud Temirbiyev and Abdurakhman Khutiev were each sentenced to 23 years in prison.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] Tsurov is currently serving his sentence in the "White Swan" prison in Perm Krai.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/1999-vladikavkaz-bombing] Magomed Tsakiyev did not live to hear his verdict — by that time, the terrorist had been killed in an armed clash.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] The **Grozny truck bombing** occurred on 27 December 2002, when three Chechen suicide bombers ran vehicles into the heavily guarded republic's government headquarters in the regional capital Grozny.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] The drivers of two vehicles reportedly wore federal military uniforms and carried official passes which allowed them through three successive military checkpoints on their way to the headquarters building.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] A guard at the fourth and final checkpoint attempted to inspect the vehicles, and began firing on the vehicles as they drove through the checkpoint towards the building.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] The explosion by the equivalent of a ton of dynamite brought down the roof and floors of the four-story building.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] The first reports mentioned as few as two dead.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] Ultimately, Chechen officials said 83 people were killed (48 on the spot) and 210 were injured.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] Several Chechen administration officials were injured in the attack, including Deputy Prime Minister Zina Batyzheva (seriously wounded) and Chechen Security Council Secretary Rudnik Dudayev.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] The head of the pro-Russian administration in Chechnya, Akhmad Kadyrov, and his Prime Minister, Mikhail Babich, were not in the building at the time.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] Colonel Ilya Shabalkin, spokesman for the joint federal forces in Chechnya, said the bombing was organized by Chechen rebel field commanders Abu al-Walid and Shamil Basayev.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] Basayev claimed responsibility for the planning and execution of the attack, saying that he personally detonated the bomb by remote control.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] Some news reports called the attack an act of terrorism, which with 83 confirmed fatalities, would have been the deadliest terrorist attack in Chechnya.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-grozny-truck-bombing] Others described the attackers as militants and rebels and not terrorists.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] The **2002 Kaspiysk bombing** occurred on 9 May 2002, an attack which ripped through the military parade to commemorate the 57th anniversary of Soviet victory in the Second World War on Lenin Street in the city of Kaspiysk, Dagestan.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Forty four people, including at least 19 soldiers were killed and 133 wounded in the explosion.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] The explosive device represented MON-50 directional landmine enhanced for greater destructive capability.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] On May 16 Kaspiysk police announced that another terrorist attack had been prevented.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Three terrorists were caught while planting a MON-100 mine, similar to that detonated on May 9.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] During the arrest, the suspects presented papers from Dagestan's Ministry of Internal affairs and said that police had no right to arrest them.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Further investigation was blocked by the Russian state security service FSB, and the director of the service, Nikolai Patrushev announced that "the arrested parties had no connection with terrorists".
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Further fate of these suspects, one of whom was identified as Rashid Dzabrailov, remains unknown.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] According to the indictment brought after the investigation, the explosion was organized by the Dagestani militant Rappani Khalilov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Khalilov allegedly sent his envoy named Kazim Abdurakhmanov to Dagestan to organize the bombing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Abdurakhmanov offered Abdulkhalim Abdulkarimov to join the plot, and Abdulkarimov agreed.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Another militant, Dzhamal Turulayev, ordered Murad Abdurazakov to build the remotely controlled land mine-based bomb.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] The bomb was delivered to the potential explosion spot by Khanali Umakhanov.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Abdulkarimov was videotaping the bomb installation, while Turulayev triggered the explosion by remote control.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] However, on 1 July 2005, the jury found Abdulkhalim Abdulkarimov and Murad Abdurazakov not guilty of participating in the bombing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] They were found guilty on other charges, such as participating in illegal armed formations, possessing weapons and counterfeiting documents, and they were sentenced to 14 years (Abdurazakov) and 11 years (Abdulkarimov) of imprisonment.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Khanali Umakhanov was also found not guilty of most of the charges he was facing in court (including terrorism) on 20 October 2005.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] He was found guilty of transporting the remote control device that triggered the bomb and sentenced to four years in prison, but the jury decided he did not know how the device was going to get used.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] The sentence was later reduced to two years on appeal and he was released.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] After release, he sued the Russian government for being tortured when in custody and unlawful prosecution.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] On 10 October 2007 the court found the government liable and awarded him 5,000,000 rubles (approx.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] The award was reduced to 3,000,000 rubles on appeal.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] Six Russian soldiers from units deployed at Buinaksk in Dagestan were also arrested for allegedly selling an anti-personnel mine to the men who carried out the attack.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] As of May 2023, none of the other people who were still wanted by the law enforcement in connection with the plot (including Turulayev and Abdurakhmanov) have been arrested.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2002-kaspiysk-bombing] The alleged mastermind, Rappani Khalilov, was killed in Dagestan on 18 September 2007.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-red-square-bombing] The **2003 Red Square bombing** was the 9 December 2003 suicide bombing on Mohovaja street in Moscow.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-red-square-bombing] According to police, a female suicide bomber set off an explosive belt on a busy street close to the Moscow Kremlin, killing six people and injuring 14.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-red-square-bombing] Moscow's mayor Yuri Luzhkov reported speculation that the bomber had intended to target the nearby Moscow City Hall or State Duma instead.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-red-square-bombing] According to the investigation, the suicide bomber was identified as Khadishat (in other sources - Khedizhi) Mangerieva, a widow of a Chechen rebel commander of Kurchaloyevsky District, Ruslan Mangeriev, who was killed during the Second Chechen War.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-red-square-bombing] One of the victims, Inga (Inna) Gizoeva, was suspected to be a helper of Mangerieva.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-red-square-bombing] After speculation, several Russian newspapers printed apologies to Gizoeva's parents.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-stavropol-train-bombing] The **2003 Stavropol train bombing** was a terrorist attack that occurred on 5 December 2003, in Yessentuki, Stavropol Krai, Russia, when an explosion on a commuter train killed at least 46 people and injured over 170 more.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-stavropol-train-bombing] A regional electric train in Stavropol Krai was commuting from Kislovodsk to Mineralnye Vody in Stavropol Krai, when a suicide bomber armed with explosives equivalent to an estimated 7 kilograms (15 pounds) worth of TNT detonated as the train departed from the station in Yessentuki.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-stavropol-train-bombing] Responsibility for the attack was immediately pointed at Chechen terrorists, who had committed previous attacks on trains on the line shortly before, including one on September 3, 2003, killing 7 and injuring more than 80.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-stavropol-train-bombing] Ibragim Israpilov, a former local official from Chechnya, was convicted in 2004 for organizing the September blast and sentenced to 20 years of imprisonment.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-stavropol-train-bombing] He is sometimes erroneously reported as being behind the December 5 bombing.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-stavropol-train-bombing] Another series of suicide bombings and other terrorist attacks in and around Chechnya and Moscow also occurred in 2003, which added to suspicion.
[src:1977-moscow-bombings/2003-stavropol-train-bombing] As of February 2023, there were no arrests or convictions for the Yessentuki attack.
